## How it builds and deploys

{% if stack_kind == 'node' %}The build tool compiles the source into `dist/`. Installs are reproducible from the committed lockfile (`npm ci`, not `npm install`).{% if static_site %} The site is served under the base path `{{ base_path }}` to match GitHub Pages deployment.{% endif %}
{% elif stack_kind == 'python' %}This is a Python project. Pin dependencies in `pyproject.toml` so environments are reproducible. The verify command runs the tests and linter before each commit.
{% elif stack_kind == 'r' %}This is an R project. Pin the environment (for example with `renv`) so it is reproducible. The verify command runs the package checks before each commit.
{% elif stack_kind == 'android' %}Compilation is delegated to CI: every push builds a debug APK on a GitHub-hosted runner (no on-device build, no signing secrets), uploaded as the `app-debug` artefact to download and sideload. SDK levels and the JDK are template variables; library versions live in the Gradle version catalogue (`gradle/libs.versions.toml`). Release signing is deferred to a later, separately scoped prompt.
{% else %}This is a static project.{% if static_site %} The site is served under the base path `{{ base_path }}` on GitHub Pages.{% else %} It builds locally with no live deployment.{% endif %}
{% endif %}
CI re-runs the build, the verify command, and a secret scan on every push, so a
broken or leaky commit is caught automatically.

## Development workflow

This repository follows the `eek-a-dev` commit-to-`main` workflow:

- one prompt equals one reviewable unit of work;
- prompt files live in `docs-dev/agent/prompts/`;
- prompt work is committed directly to `main` using the exact prompt filename as
  the commit message;
- do not create feature branches or pull requests unless explicitly instructed;
- run the project verify command and prompt checks before committing.

Start with `docs-dev/agent/how_to_use.md` for the daily workflow.

